Thank you, Mr./Madam Chair, judges, and the opposing team.

I am the second speaker of the Proposition. In this speech, I will respond to the first speaker of the Opposition and further prove that death is a regret of life.

First, the Opposition says death gives life a boundary and makes life meaningful. We agree that limited time can make us cherish life. But this only proves life is precious. It does not prove death is not a regret. For example, a beautiful song may become more moving because it is short, but if it is suddenly stopped before the last note, we still feel sorry. In the same way, death may remind us to value time, but it also takes away the time we still need.

Second, the Opposition says death is natural, so it completes life. But natural does not mean perfect. Illness, aging, and separation are also natural, but we do not call them beautiful or complete. A natural ending can still bring regret. Our side does not deny the life cycle. We only point out that when death comes, it permanently stops a person's plans, growth, love, and choices. This loss is real.

Third, the Opposition says memories and achievements can continue after death. But memory is not the same as life itself. A photo of parents cannot replace their company. A story about a friend cannot replace one more conversation with that friend. Spirit may remain, but the person has lost all future possibilities. That is exactly why death is regretful.

So today's key question is not whether death gives life meaning. The real question is: when death ends unfinished wishes and breaks living relationships forever, should we call that complete or regretful? Our answer is clear. It is regretful.

Therefore, we firmly believe that death is a regret of life. Thank you.

= answer

I'm not equating naturalness with regret. Death can be a release from pain, but that does not erase the regret it brings. Even a peaceful natural death ends possibilities: future love, growth, choices, and unfinished bonds. Relief describes the manner of dying; regret describes what is lost.
